new='PASSAGES["Level 21"]=[{title:"The Anthropocene",text:"Geologists divide Earth\'s history into epochs defined by characteristic changes in the stratigraphic record — the layers of rock, sediment, and ice that preserve evidence of past conditions. The current official epoch, the Holocene, began approximately 11,700 years ago at the end of the last ice age and has been characterized by unusual climatic stability that enabled the development of agriculture and complex civilization. A growing number of scientists argue that human activity has so profoundly altered Earth\'s systems that we have entered a new epoch: the Anthropocene, or the age of humans. The proposed markers are numerous and striking. Radionuclides from nuclear weapons testing are detectable in sediment layers worldwide. Plastics have been found in the deepest ocean trenches. The biomass of domesticated animals now vastly exceeds that of wild mammals. Atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations are higher than at any point in at least three million years. Species extinction rates are estimated to be one hundred to one thousand times background rates, leading many biologists to describe the current moment as the sixth mass extinction. The Anthropocene has not been formally ratified by the International Union of Geological Sciences, partly due to debates about when it began, but the concept has moved from specialist journals into mainstream discourse as a framework for understanding the scale of human impact on planetary systems.",qs:["What criteria do geologists use to define geological epochs?","What evidence do scientists cite for the Anthropocene?","Why does the author note that the Anthropocene has not been formally ratified?","What does the concept of the Anthropocene suggest about human responsibility to future generations?"]},{title:"The Limits of Language",text:"Language is the medium through which humans communicate, think, and construct shared reality. But it is also a system with structural limitations that shape — and in some cases constrain — what can be thought and expressed. The Sapir-Whorf hypothesis, in its strong form, proposes that the language one speaks determines the thoughts one can think: that speakers of different languages inhabit different cognitive universes. The strong form is generally rejected by contemporary linguists, but a weaker version — that language influences cognition without fully determining it — has substantial empirical support. Russian speakers, who have separate basic terms for light blue and dark blue, are faster at discriminating between those colours in perceptual tasks than English speakers, who use a single term. The Pirahã people of the Amazon, whose language lacks number words beyond one, two, and many, perform differently on certain numerical tasks than speakers of languages with precise number systems. Philosopher Ludwig Wittgenstein\'s observation that the limits of my language are the limits of my world captures something important, even if it overstates the case. Every professional domain — law, medicine, mathematics, music — develops specialized vocabulary precisely because ordinary language is insufficient to describe its distinctions with adequate precision. The question of what cannot be said in any language, and whether such things can be thought, remains genuinely open.",qs:["What is the difference between the strong and weak versions of the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis?","What empirical evidence supports the weak version of the hypothesis?","What does Wittgenstein\'s observation mean and what are its limits?","Can you think of an experience or idea that you find difficult to express in language?"]},{title:"The Future of Democracy",text:"Liberal democracy, the system combining competitive elections, constitutional rights, separation of powers, and protection of civil liberties, expanded dramatically after the Cold War. Political scientist Francis Fukuyama famously declared in 1989 that history had ended — that liberal democracy had proven itself the final form of human government. The subsequent decades have complicated that thesis considerably. Freedom House, which tracks political rights and civil liberties globally, has recorded seventeen consecutive years of democratic decline as of the early 2020s. The retreat of democracy has not primarily taken the form of military coups and sudden authoritarian seizures of power, as in the twentieth century, but of gradual erosion from within — a process political scientists call democratic backsliding. Elected leaders in Hungary, Turkey, India, Brazil, and the United States have used legal mechanisms, institutional appointments, and control of information environments to weaken checks and balances, suppress opposition, and consolidate power while maintaining the procedural appearance of democracy. The vulnerability of democratic systems to this kind of internal corrosion reflects a structural feature: democracy depends on norms and conventions that are powerful when respected but have no automatic enforcement mechanism when violated. The future of democracy may depend less on formal institutions than on the willingness of citizens, opposition parties, courts, and media to defend them.",qs:["What does democratic backsliding mean and how does it differ from traditional authoritarianism?","What structural vulnerability of democracy does the passage identify?","Why did Fukuyama\'s end of history thesis prove premature?","What do you think citizens can do to strengthen democratic institutions in their own countries?"]}];\n'
